🚀 Complete Backend (Node.js + Express + MongoDB)
📌 Overview

This project covers backend development fundamentals using:

Node.js

Express.js

REST APIs

MongoDB

Mongoose

Postman (API testing)

It explains how to create a server, build APIs, connect a database, and store data permanently.

🖥️ What is Backend?

Backend is responsible for:

Handling server logic

Managing database

Creating APIs

Processing client requests

Sending responses

🔁 Request–Response Cycle
Client → Request → Server → Database → Server → Response → Client

Frontend sends request → Backend processes it → Database stores/fetches data → Backend sends response.

🌐 What is a Server?

A server is a program that listens for client requests and sends responses.

Example:

Browser sends request to localhost:3000

Server responds with data

🟢 Node.js

Node.js is a JavaScript runtime that allows us to run JavaScript outside the browser.

Why Node.js?

Fast (V8 engine)

Non-blocking (asynchronous)

Good for APIs

Uses JavaScript everywhere

Check Installation
node -v
npm -v
📦 NPM (Node Package Manager)

NPM is used to manage packages (libraries).

Initialize Project
npm init -y

This creates:

package.json
Install Dependencies
npm install express
Install Development Dependency
npm install nodemon --save-dev
📁 Basic Folder Structure
project/
│
├── node_modules/
├── package.json
├── server.js
├── app.js

server.js → Starts server

app.js → Routes & logic

node_modules → Installed packages

⚡ Express.js

Express is a minimal framework built on Node.js that simplifies backend development.

Basic Server Setup
const express = require("express");
const app = express();

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log("Server running on port 3000");
});

Visit:

http://localhost:3000
🔀 Routing

Routes define how server responds to requests.

Example Route
app.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.send("Hello World");
});
🌍 HTTP Methods
Method	Purpose
GET	Get data
POST	Create data
PUT	Update data (full)
PATCH	Update data (partial)
DELETE	Delete data
🔌 REST API Principles

Use proper HTTP methods

Use meaningful route names

Send JSON data

Keep APIs stateless

Example:

GET     /notes
POST    /notes
DELETE  /notes/:id
📝 Notes API (Without Database)

Initially, data is stored in memory using an array.

const notes = [];
Middleware to Parse JSON
app.use(express.json());
Create Note
app.post("/notes", (req, res) => {
  const note = req.body;
  notes.push(note);
  res.json(note);
});
Get Notes
app.get("/notes", (req, res) => {
  res.json(notes);
});

⚠ Problem: Data disappears when server restarts.

🗄️ Database

A database stores data permanently.

Two types:

SQL (MySQL, PostgreSQL)

NoSQL (MongoDB)

This project uses MongoDB (NoSQL).

🍃 MongoDB

MongoDB stores data in:

Database

Collections

Documents (JSON-like format)

Structure:

Database
 └── Collection
       └── Documents
☁ MongoDB Atlas

MongoDB Atlas is a cloud-based MongoDB service.

Steps:

Create account

Create cluster

Get connection string

Connect to backend

Example Connection String:

mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster.mongodb.net/dbname
🔗 Connecting MongoDB with Mongoose
Install Mongoose
npm install mongoose
Connect to Database
const mongoose = require("mongoose");

mongoose.connect("your_connection_string")
  .then(() => console.log("Database Connected"))
  .catch(err => console.log(err));
🧩 Schema

Schema defines the structure of data.

const mongoose = require("mongoose");

const noteSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  title: String,
  description: String
});
🏗 Model

Model connects schema with MongoDB collection.

const Note = mongoose.model("Note", noteSchema);
📝 Notes API (With Database)
Create Note
app.post("/notes", async (req, res) => {
  const note = await Note.create(req.body);
  res.json(note);
});
Get Notes
app.get("/notes", async (req, res) => {
  const notes = await Note.find();
  res.json(notes);
});

Now data is stored permanently in MongoDB.

🔄 Final Backend Flow
Frontend
   ↓
API Request
   ↓
Express Server
   ↓
MongoDB Database
   ↓
Response to Client
